subCards.title: 20 Beautiful Baby Names From the 1940s That Parents Will Love Today
subCards.abstract: Vintage and cool! If the 1940s could be characterized by one world event, it would be World War II — and the period of postwar changes that followed it. That includes what's been called a Baby Boom, which means that parents in the '40s needed to think of a whole lot of baby names. Now, those '40s babies could be grandmas and grandpas, inspiring the names of the newborns in Generation Beta. Then again, there are some vintage names that will just never come back around, no matter how cute they sound. The Social Security Administration (SSA) helps keep track of which names are the most popular girl names and the most popular boy names, which ones are rising or falling in popularity, and which ones will continue to be obscure. These are the most popular baby names of the 1940s, compared to their SSA rankings today. Some have stayed on top, while others have come and gone with the trends, but they're all worth considering for the next gen of happy babies.

slides.title: Mary
slides.body:
SSA ranking in the 1940s: 1
SSA ranking today: 135
Meaning: "drop of the sea," "bitterness," or "beloved"

It's hard to overstate the grip the name Mary had in the early half of the 20th century. The name has been somewhere in the top five most popular names every year from 1967 going back to 1924, when the SSA first started keeping track of top-five names. And yet today, in a world dominated by Olivias, Sophias and Emmas, Mary has fallen outside the top 100 — but will it ascend to the top spots again? With so many Marys out there, there are many notable people to act as a namesake, including Mary Welsh Hemingway, a journalist in World War II and wife of Earnest Hemingway.

slides.body:

SSA ranking today: 4
Meaning: "supplanter"

James is a true classic, standing the test of time: It was a top-five name in the 1940s, and it remains a top-five name today. There's nothing old-fashioned about it, looking as fitting on daycare cubbies in the 2020s as it did on movie marquees in the 1940s, especially when actors like James Mason — who starred in nearly two dozen films in the 1940s — were on the screen.

slides.title: Linda
slides.body:
SSA ranking in the 1940s: 2
SSA ranking today: 842
Meaning: "pretty"

If Mary had to pass the baton, it would be passed to Linda. The name Linda did not appear as one of the top names of the 1930s, but it would increase in popularity throughout the '40s until it claimed the No. 1 spot from 1947 to 1952, and remained in the top five until 1963. Perhaps they were all inspired by The Mask of Zorro actress Linda Darnell, who certainly embodies the name's meaning of "pretty." Linda is currently on the wane, hitting the SSA's list of the names that have decreased in popularity over the last year, but that just means it's fair game for any parent who wants to snap it up.

subCards.title: A New Island Has Formed Overnight Following a Seafloor Eruption
subCards.abstract: A New Island Has Formed Overnight Following a Seafloor Eruption

slides.title: What Caused the Eruption?
slides.body:
The dramatic eruption that led to the island's formation was a result of tectonic plates shifting beneath the ocean's surface. Imagine the Earth's crust as a giant puzzle, with pieces that are always in motion.

When these pieces, or plates, move, they can create gaps where magma from the Earth's mantle escapes. This upward surge of magma results in an explosive volcanic eruption, spewing gases and molten rock into the ocean.

Over time, as this material accumulates, it can rise above sea level, giving birth to new landforms like islands.

slides.title: The Formation of the Island
slides.body:
The birth of the island was nothing short of a spectacle. As volcanic ash and lava poured into the surrounding waters, they quickly solidified, forming a new landmass.

Initially, this fledgling island was small, but it rapidly expanded as more material erupted from the seafloor. Within mere hours, the island grew large enough to be spotted by passing ships and aircraft.

This swift formation is a testament to the immense power of volcanic activity and the formidable forces operating beneath the Earth's crust.

cards.title: The McDonnell Douglas MD-12: The Double-Decker Superjumbo
cards.abstract: In the early 1990s, McDonnell Douglas unveiled the MD-12, a bold double-decker superjumbo designed to rival the Boeing 747. Promising capacity for over 500 passengers and lower fuel burn per seat, the MD-12 aimed to dominate transatlantic and high-density Asian routes. Despite heavy marketing, financial risks and lack of airline interest doomed the project. A brief partnership with Taiwan Aerospace collapsed, and by 1993 the program was shelved. Though never built, the MD-12 concept foreshadowed the later Airbus A380, offering a glimpse of what might have been.

cards.title: Building The Perfect Aircraft - What Would It Look Like & Where Would It Fly
cards.abstract: This video imagines the perfect commercial aircraft—one that balances passenger comfort, efficiency, and profitability for airlines. With seating for 200 to 250 passengers, the design favors a narrow-body jet capable of flying up to 5,000 nautical miles, opening new transatlantic and Asia-Pacific routes. Designed for low-cost carriers, it sacrifices wide-body comfort for fuel efficiency and operational flexibility. Cargo capacity is limited but includes a tail-loading freighter version. Inspired by the Boeing 757, the concept shows why there’s still demand for a mid-sized aircraft built for long, thin routes.

slides.body:

slides.title: 19. Marie Curie: The Pioneer of Radioactivity
slides.body:
Marie Curie was the first woman to win a Nobel Prize and the only person to win in two different sciences (Physics and Chemistry). Her work on radioactivity laid the foundation for modern physics and medicine.

She discovered polonium and radium, changing cancer treatment forever. Even today, her research influences X-rays and radiation therapy.

Curie’s relentless curiosity made her one of history’s greatest scientists.

subCards.abstract: Conservative Leader Pierre Poilievre says he’ll ensure multiple-murderers die in jail by becoming the first Canadian prime minister to override charter rights by invoking the notwithstanding clause.

cards.title: Why Solar Panels Are Becoming a Toxic Nightmare
cards.abstract: Why Solar Panels Are Becoming a Toxic Nightmare

slides.title: The Environmental Cost of Production
slides.body:
Solar panels are often hailed as the champions of clean energy, but beneath their shiny surface lies an environmental conundrum. The process of manufacturing solar panels involves the use of hazardous materials such as cadmium, lead, and silicon.

As per the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA), these substances can seep into the surrounding environment during production, contaminating soil and water. In 2021, it was noted that approximately 20% of the world's solar panels were made using these harmful materials.

The extraction of raw materials necessary for solar panel production further exacerbates ecological damage. From mining activities, which emit a significant amount of carbon, to habitat destruction, the environmental cost is substantial.

This aspect of solar panel production is often overshadowed by the perception of solar energy as a purely green solution.

slides.title: End-of-Life Disposal Challenges
slides.body:
Solar panels are not eternal; they typically last between 25 to 30 years before they reach the end of their useful life. Once expired, these panels become waste, posing a significant environmental challenge.

Unlike organic materials that decompose, solar panels are not biodegradable, contributing to a growing waste problem. The International Energy Agency (IEA) reported that by 2030, the planet could be dealing with about 78 million metric tons of solar panel waste.

The majority of landfills are ill-equipped to manage this type of waste, leading to the risk of toxic substances leaching into the ground and water systems. This looming waste management issue is a stark contradiction to the eco-friendly image solar panels are supposed to represent.

slides.title: Recycling Issues
slides.body:
Recycling solar panels seems like a logical solution to the waste problem, but the reality is more complex. According to the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL), only around 10% of solar panels are currently recycled.

The recycling process itself is intricate and expensive, often recovering just a fraction of the materials. This inefficiency raises questions about the overall sustainability of solar energy.

As the adoption of solar panels continues to grow, the lack of robust recycling infrastructure could lead to an environmental crisis. The challenge is not just to recycle more but to do so in a way that is economically viable and environmentally beneficial.
